.TH WIPE-SAFE-AT 1 "APRIL 2016" WIPE-SAFE-AT 1
.SH NAME
wipe-safe-at	-	Wipe Safe - Avoid Typo
.SH SYNOPSIS
.br
.B wipe-safe-at 
.I [options] [path to device | device name]
.br

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B wipe-safe-at 
is a bash script with additional safety checks before starting wiping tools.
.br
By default all safety checks are set to maximum. 
Without option "--nd" or "--no-dry-run" it will only show what can be done.
.br
You can use either only a device name or a full path to it. 
.B wipe-safe-at
sdX(Y)
.B wipe-safe-at
[options] /dev/sdX(Y)

.SH OPTIONS
.B --help
- show help message
.br
.IP "\fB\-a , --add-wipe-loop \fR[number\fR]"
- set amount of additional loops for option --order
.br
Defaut = 0
.IP "\fB\-o , --order \fR[order of methods\fR]"
- set order of wiping commands
.br	
Example: --order ddr,ddz,cpr,cpz
.IP "\fB\--sm , --show-me \fR[grep pattern\fR]"
- searching content in this script, 
.br
    supporting grep syntax and should be used only as the first option.
.br	
Helpful to list available patterns that can be used with command "--order"
.br	
and find places where you can add own tools.
.br	
Example:
.br
.B	wipe-safe-at \fR--show-me -e \fB methods\fR -e \fB NO_DRY\fR -e \fB OPTIONS
	  
-IP -c , --confirm [yes/1 , no/0]	- disable confirmation before continue
Default = yes
.IP "\fB\-s , --safety [0/disable , 1/low , 2/max]"
- set safety level
	0/disable	- will not check if any of the partitions is mounted
	1/low       - will stop only if the destination partition is mounted
	2/max       - will stop if at least one partition is mounted
Default = max
.IP "\fB\--nd , --no-dry-run"
- By default it only shows what can be done
.SH ADD OWN TOOLS
.IP WARNING !!!!!! 
.IP PLEASE KEEP SAFETY SYNTAX WHEN ADDING OWN WIPING TOOLS
.br
This should be infront of each wiping tool:
.br
.P [[ "$NO_DRY" == "YES" ]] &&
and followed the bash syntax for 
.br
case ... esac
.br
        command1 | command2 )
[[\fB\"$NO_DRY"\fR\==\fR\"YES"\fR\]]\fR\&&\fR\
tool to use
\fR\        ;;

wipe-safe-at --show-me -e methods -e NO_DRY
And you will get an output of where them are located in the script
\fR.........
\fR.........
\fR LineNumber:	dd-random | ddr | dd ) # methods: wipe partition
\fR LineNumber:[[ "$NO_DRY" == "YES" ]] && dd if=/dev/urandom bs="${Use_Logical_Block_Size}" count="${Partition_Sectors}" oflag=direct iflag=nocache -of="/dev/${Path_To_Partition##*/}"
\fR LineNumber:	dd-zero | ddz ) # methods: wipe partition
\fR LineNumber:[[ "$NO_DRY" == "YES" ]] && dd if=/dev/zero bs="${Use_Logical_Block_Size}" count="${Partition_Sectors}" oflag=direct iflag=nocache of="/dev/${Path_To_Partition##*/}"
\fR .........
\fR .........
\fR LineNumber:	dd-random | ddr | dd ) # methods: wipe device
\fR LineNumber:[[ "$NO_DRY" == "YES" ]] && dd if=/dev/urandom bs="${Use_Physical_Block_Size}"  count="${Use_Device_Physical_Sectors}" oflag=direct iflag=nocache of=/dev/"${Main_Device_Name##*/}"
\fR LineNumber:	dd-zero | ddz ) # methods: wipe device
\fR LineNumber:[[ "$NO_DRY" == "YES" ]] && dd if=/dev/zero bs="${Use_Physical_Block_Size}"  count="${Use_Device_Physical_Sectors}" oflag=direct iflag=nocache of=/dev/"${Main_Device_Name##*/}"
\fR .........
\fR .........

.SH USAGE

Only to preview what can be done don't use one of the following options: --no-dry-run or --nd in combination with option --order
First use option --order to chose which of the tools you want to use. To see currently available use as the first option:

wipe-safe --show-me -e NO_DRY -e methods
Then preview how it will look like when starting wiping. This example will start wiping first with dd and /dev/urandom as a source, after that will start dd with the source /dev/zero. The order of tools must be separated with: ,

wipe-safe-at --order ddr,ddz /dev/sdX(Y)
To use same order of tools more than once you can use option --add-wipe-loop or -a. This example will preview wiping with additional 33 rounds the combination of urandom/zero/urandom:

wipe-safe-at --order ddr,ddz,ddr --add-wipe-loop 33 /dev/sdX(Y)

Not recommended but to disable all security options

wipe-safe-at --safety 0 --confirm 0 --no-dry-run --order ddr,ddz /dev/sda

